<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>05 April 2005</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence submitted by Christian Solidarity Worldwide </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Brief </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> of key points</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Christian Solidarity Worldwide (CSW) believes the Department for International Development (DFID) should prioritise the following areas in its programme for Burma in the coming period:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Inter-religious dialogue and reconciliation initiatives to address religious conflict;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Humanitarian assistance for those affected by conflict, particularly the internally displaced in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kachin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Arakan</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> states;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Support for the victims of grave human rights violations, including but not limited to former child soldiers, victims of rape and sexual abuse, former political prisoners, victims of torture, forced labour and other abuses;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Initiatives to promote concepts of equal rights and Burma as a multi-ethnic, multi-religious society; </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Civil society development, particularly among the ethnic nationalities;</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.03pt; padding-left:7.97pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Conflict resolution and the establishment of a genuine, inclusive, nationwide peace process.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Christian Solidarity Worldwide (CSW) is a human rights advocacy organisation specialising in freedom of religion or belief. CSW has focused on Burma for more than twenty years, with a particular interest in the situation of the ethnic nationalities.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> CSW travels regularly to Burma, both inside the country and to the borders with Thailand, India, China and Bangladesh. In particular, CSW has considerable knowledge of the situation in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kachin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, Chin, Karen, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Karenni</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and Shan states, and the plight of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Rohingya</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> people of northern </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Arakan</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> state. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">CSW’s East Asia Team leader, Benedict Rogers, has personally made over 40 visits to Burma and its borderlands, written three books on Burma including </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Burma: A Nation at the Crossroads </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">(Random House, 2012), and regularly contributes to international media, including </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Wall Street Journal </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The International Herald Tribune</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">. He has also testified at hearings in the US Congress, the European Parliament and the Japanese Parliament as well as in previous inquiries in the House of Commons. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> For further information and copies of CSW reports, please contact Benedict Rogers at </span><a href="mailto:ben@csw.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">ben@csw.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt"> or visit the Burma section of </span><a href="http://www.csw.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.csw.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Over the past two years, Burma has seen some significant changes. Since President </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Thein</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Sein</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and the Chairperson of the National League for Democracy (NLD), Daw </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Aung</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> San </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Suu</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kyi</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">, met for the first time in August 2011, a series of reforms have been </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">introduced, including the release of the majority of political prisoners, increased freedom for civil society, the media and political actors, the election to Parliament of NLD candidates, and the establishment of ceasefire agreements with almost all the ethnic armed resistance organisations. These changes are very welcome and should be recognised, and encouraged.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">However, there is still a very </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">very</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> long way to go, and the transition is extremely fragile. Three issues represent particularly serious concerns: the continuing conflict in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kachin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> State; the persecution of the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Rohingyas</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">; and the emergence of a militant Buddhist </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Burman</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> nationalist movement with a wider campaign of hatred and violence against Muslims. The changes introduced so far can be described primarily as a change in atmosphere, rather than a fundamental change in system. Genuine change will only come when all remaining political prisoners are released, repressive laws are repealed or reformed, the war against the </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kachin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> stops, a genuine nationwide peace process with the ethnic nationalities, involving a political dialogue, is established, inter-religious tensions are addressed and the constitution is amended. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">CSW believes the Department for International Development (DFID) can play a key role in helping Burma to address these challenges, by prioritising humanitarian assistance to the internally displaced people in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kachin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> State and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Arakan</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> State; increasing support for civil society, particularly human rights documentation and advocacy work; and by providing support for initiatives which promote inter-religious dialogue, freedom of religion or belief and inter-religious harmony, at national, regional and grassroots levels; and providing support for the rehabilitation of former child soldiers, political prisoners, victims of sexual violence and victims of other human rights violations.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Priority focus: </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Ethnic and religious conflict</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Establishing a genuine, inclusive, nationwide peace process, involving a political dialogue, is critical to the success of any transition to a more open, democratic and peaceful future for Burma. The current fragile, preliminary ceasefires represent just the first step towards a lasting solution, and unless they develop into a political dialogue as part of a peace process, they will not lead to real peace. Key to securing this peace process is the role of civil society among the ethnic nationalities, including women’s organisations, ethnic relief groups working with the internally displaced, representatives of refugees and ethnic human rights documentation and advocacy organisations. DFID should increase financial support and other means of empowerment for civil society among the ethnic nationalities, and initiatives to enhance communication, engagement, dialogue and partnership between different ethnic civil society groups and between ethnic groups and </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Burman</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> democracy groups.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">The humanitarian needs of those affected by decades of conflict in the ethnic states must be a priority for DFID. In particular, there is a need for further humanitarian assistance for internally displaced people in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Kachin</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> and northern Shan states, </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">especially those in areas outside Government control, and for internally displaced people in </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Arakan</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> State, displaced following the violence in June and October 2012.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.31pt; padding-left:4.69pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">DFID should also consider ways to help other victims of conflict, particularly former child soldiers, former political prisoners, victims of rape and sexual violence, victims of forced labour and torture. This might include funding for rehabilitation and educational projects.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">In addition to prioritising the situation of the ethnic nationalities, there is an urgent need to address religious conflict in society, which has emerged over the past year as perhaps the predominant threat to Burma’s stability and prospects of a successful transition to a freer, more open and more peaceful society. The rise of the militant Buddhist </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Burman</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> nationalist movement, “969”, and its anti-Muslim hate propaganda, resulting in a wave of horrific violence, is a major threat to inter-religious harmony. There are early warning signs that this could spread to affect not only Muslims, but Christians and other non-Buddhists as well, tearing at the fabric of a multi-religious and multi-ethnic Burma. DFID should prioritise provision of funding for initiatives which promote inter-religious dialogue and reconciliation, public awareness campaigns to counter hate speech, education in principles of freedom of religion or belief (as set out in Article 18 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights), and promoting better understanding of the practices of the different religions in Burma, thereby addressing misunderstandings and some of the core causes of inter-religious conflict.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Supporting the media is important, as freedom for the press expands. However, some media have contributed to religious intolerance and hate speech through their coverage of issues, and so providing support for training and education in responsible journalism and media ethics would be important.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Conclusions and Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">CSW welcomes the increased support DFID has provided to civil society in recent years, and the provision of humanitarian assistance to internally displaced people. Since the previous Select Committee inquiry in 2007, to which CSW provided both written and oral evidence, DFID’s contribution to Burma’s democratisation and development has increased significantly, both in financial terms and in breadth and scale. CSW welcomes the increased priority which DFID places on Burma.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Within DFID’s increased bilateral programme for Burma, however, CSW believes there is a need for greater prioritisation of the two major challenges facing the country, namely the ethnic conflict and the inter-religious conflict. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">CSW welcomes DFID’s initiation of economic governance work, particularly in regard to extractive industries transparency, natural resource management, public financial management and responsible investment. However, CSW believes the Select Committee should scrutinise carefully the value of DFID’s funding for the Myanmar </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">Centre for Responsible Business, to ensure that such initiatives do deliver results in terms of promoting responsible and ethical investment, and are not simply providing a public relations service for businesses in Burma. While responsible investment is certainly a major concern as Burma opens up to international business, CSW believes initiatives in this field should be transparent, deliver value for money and results, and should have a measurable impact. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">While there are many competing and urgent needs in Burma, CSW believes addressing both the causes and the effects of conflict, both ethnic and religious, should be the priority, because without progress towards a genuine peace, harmony, the rule of law and respect for human rights, a transition to real democracy and development in Burma will not progress. DFID has a unique and vital role to play in contributing to these, as well as </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt"> many other aspects of Burma’s transition.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>